headline: Striking Starbucks workers aim to expand walkout to 300 US stores
summary: Starbucks (SBUX) baristas are continuing to strike as part of a planned five-day walkout — which originally started in Los Angeles, Chicago, and Seattle last — over contract negotiations. The walkout caused around 60 stores to close as the strike is expected to expand to more than 300 locations across the US, according to the Starbucks Workers United union. Morning Brief hosts Brad Smith and Josh Lipton discuss more on the ongoing situation for Starbucks as chairman and chief executive officer Brian Niccol works to address the coffee chain's range of cultural and operational issues. Catch Yahoo Finance's interview with Starbucks CEO Brian Niccol from November, where the chief executive stated his intent to “fix the parameters” around getting the operating experience for employees to match the customer experience. To watch more expert insights and analysis on the latest market action, check out more Morning Brief here. This post was written by Josh Lynch

headline: Starbucks strike to expand to over 300 US stores on Christmas Eve, union says
summary: (Reuters) -A strike at Starbucks will expand to over 300 U.S. stores on Tuesday, with more than 5,000 workers expected to walk off the job before the five-day work stoppage ends later on Christmas Eve, the workers' union said.  Starbucks Workers United, representing employees at 525 stores nationwide, said more than 60 U.S. stores across 12 major cities, including New York, Los Angeles, Boston and Seattle, were shut on Monday.  Talks between Starbucks and the union had hit an impasse with unresolved issues over wages, staffing and schedules, leading to the strike that began on Friday.
